The Independent Gambling Authority is an independent statutory commission reponsible for the integrity of the commercial gambling products lawfully provided to people in South Australia, and to ensure that those products are provided responsibly and safely.

Specific statutory responsibilities include--
+ oversight of operational (inspection and compliance) regulation by the Lioquor and Gambling Commissioner; 
+ mandatory advertising and responsibly gambling codes of practice;
+ disciplinary regulation of wagering licensees and operators and of the casino licensee;
+ research;
+ barring (exclusion) of problem gamblers;
+ problem gambling family protection orders.

The Association has as aims and objectives to:

- Uniting public, semi-public or private companies, the holding of both a monopole and a license or concession of African States to operate games of chance, prognoses and assimilated.
- Encourage mutual assistance in the technical and the educational level among members of the Association.
- Participate in African economic integration through the establishment of the Pan-African Games;
- Participate in socio-economic achievements in priority areas such as education, security, civil protection, health, culture and sport, the fight against unemployment and poverty through creating jobs and income generating activities;
- Organize seminars, congresses, conferences, general meetings and consultation frameworks for capacity reinforcement;
- Forge bonds of solidarity with sister associations of lotteries and other organizations with similar aims all over the world;
- Develop norms, standards and codes of good conduct to serve as repositories to which members must comply (ISO, responsible gaming, WLA standard, security standard etc ...).
- As part of pursuing its aims and objectives, the Association respects the territorial integrity, public order and morality.

The Bermuda Casino Gaming Commission commenced operations in 2015 based on the enactment of the Casino Gaming Act 2014. The organization is responsible for regulating the casino gaming industry in Bermuda based on five key principles.

-  Owners, vendors, managers, employees, and sources of finance should be free from any inappropriate past or present associations and behaviours, and uphold high ethical standards;
-  Operators should possess sound operational and financial controls;
-  The games offered should be fair, honest, and operate with a high level of security and integrity;
-  All fees, taxes, and related payments, should be appropriately accounted for and paid; and
-  Controls should be in place to protect the vulnerable.
